observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct concerned officials and employees to submit the following:

Trip monitoring or accomplishment reports to provide assurance that services were rendered by drivers;

Memoranda of Agreement between the LGU and transport associations contracted to provide transport services to establish the legality of the agreement;

Copies of the Certificates of Public Convenience (CPC) of jeepney operators as assurance that they are authorized to operate as common carriers;

Proof that passengers catered by drivers whose services were charged against the BGCM were frontliners and/or LGU personnel in compliance with LBC No. 125 dated April 7, 2020; and



Henceforth, strictly comply with guidelines on the utilization of funds received for specific purposes to ensure the proper and prudent application of resources.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct concerned officials and employees to:
a. Submit a justification on the above-listed deficiencies;
b. Design a well-planned procurement program that would eliminate the use of alternative methods in the procurement of catering services;
c. Henceforth, ensure that Purchase Requests and Requests for Quotations for meals are duly supported with food specifications and payments for meals are based on the actual number of event attendees;
d. Henceforth, comply with the posting requirements in Section 54.3 of the IRR of RA No. 9184;
e. Henceforth, submit Purchase Orders within the prescribed period, and the Acceptance and Inspection Reports of consumable and perishable items to this Office within 24 hours from acceptance of the items delivered.
f. Submit the necessary procurement documents pertaining to the payments for meals of returning residents undergoing quarantine for April to July 2021. Henceforth, procurement of catering services should be duly supported with the requisite documents.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to Management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2022-05 dated April 1, 2022.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require:
a. The responsible officers to immediately submit the required documents to avoid suspension of transactions;
b. The concerned officials/heads of office to ensure compliance with the submission of complete and sufficient supporting papers on all claims against government funds as required under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001, and Budget Circular No. 2007-1 so that validity thereof could be properly established and validated;
c. The Municipal Accountant to ensure that the payment for honoraria be remitted to the respective mother agencies of government personnel with the corresponding certificates on the taxes withheld and that honoraria paid to resource persons and lecturers are properly computed in accordance with Budget Circular No 2007-1; and
d. The Municipal Accountant to ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from payments for honoraria and professional fees, and the same are remitted to the BIR within the prescribed period.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to Management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2022-08 dated April 6, 2022.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct concerned officials and employees to:

Provide a written justification on the deviation noted, and an approved program design with specific guidelines regarding the procurement and distribution of the rice incentive to LGU employees, which was contrary to COA Circular No. 94-013 and Executive Order No. 081-A, Series of 2020;

Submit a revised project proposal explicitly including the procurement of 476 sacks rice for distribution to 121 LGU personnel among the PPAs, duly approved by the IPG, otherwise the amount shall be duly refunded by accountable officials and employees; 

Submit the daily time records and office orders of employees who were given the rice incentive as basis for services rendered; and

Comply with all policy guidelines and regulations in the implementation of programs funded through inter-agency assistance by utilizing funds for its intended purpose to avoid disqualification on future projects and programs.
